Cell[TextData[{
 "and compare with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumSimilarity"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "f0b84872-5f46-4371-a230-2c392acea028"],
 ", which returns one for states that agree up to a global phase:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a5aa897e-20a5-4e5e-811e-0916eeafe8eb"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"QuantumSimilarity", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"frame", "[", "\"\<State\>\"", "]"}], ",", " ", "dense"}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[80]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"cc8fa92b-b019-48d4-9395-0f2ebcee4f58"],

Cell[BoxData["1"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[80]= ",ExpressionUUID->"c924e878-b5fc-491e-a079-1c40e3e97c3c"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "What the frame does not yet do is ",
 StyleBox["compress", "TI"],
 ". The true stabilizer rank of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["t", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e0818e48-5886-485d-998b-3134026e7c1b"],
 " magic states grows like ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["2", 
   StyleBox[
    RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", "t"}], "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "852e6277-06e0-4e7c-af2e-26c40f833c55"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "\[TildeTilde]", "0.4"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cee622f4-97ce-49ac-91c2-5b80d065b1ff"],
 ", far below the naive ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["2", 
   StyleBox["t", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "836d82e9-8251-4a8a-8973-cb63139ba47f"],
 ", and the framework keeps every term. So the frame is exact and faithful \
for a handful of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["T", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e821c056-bed5-4f45-b6d5-63cb5924f771"],
 " gates and is the right object to reason about rank, but it is not a \
scalable magic-state simulator; for that the terms must be merged, which is \
the Bravyi-Gosset program."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4fccc198-e1f9-4441-8194-12e4adedd74a"],

Cell["Clifford channels", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"d1e20213-7e51-4e00-a332-4bf41987bc95"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Open-system Clifford dynamics, the maps that send stabilizer states to \
stabilizer states, are encoded by a Boolean Choi tableau in the framework's [",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "CliffordChannel"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "3189f4a0-bdc5-45d7-92b5-76eff67ad720"],
 "], following Yashin. The identity channel on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["n", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f64ceb2b-e769-4c6b-83e2-85299270d163"],
 " qubits has a tableau of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e7def7d6-e115-4f51-a695-b16a0eabfc8f"],
 " rows:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"634708ab-147a-44c2-91a1-b2b94a92c092"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"CliffordChannel", "[", 
   RowBox[{"\"\<Identity\>\"", ",", " ", "3"}], "]"}], "[", "\"\<Rank\>\"", 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[81]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"e06ff348-2edc-4593-90ef-9e2c27229a94"],

Cell[BoxData["6"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[81]= ",ExpressionUUID->"a8f9207e-fd9c-4c5d-8cab-b1a7cb354ae5"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
A pure stabilizer state is itself a state-preparation Clifford channel, whose \
tableau is the state's stabilizer half. Converting the Bell state to its \
channel recovers its two parity-check rows:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c8e073fc-62f5-40e9-90f2-0dc43cee3b30"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"CliffordChannel", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliStabilizer", "[", "2", "]"}], "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"\"\<H\>\"", ",", " ", "\"\<CNOT\>\""}], "}"}], "]"}], "]"}], 
   "[", "\"\<Tableau\>\"", "]"}], " ", "//", " ", "MatrixForm"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[82]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"cb2c0dc4-9d0e-4499-8962-bea662789207"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[
  RowBox[{"(", "\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
     {"1", "1", "0", "0", "0"},
     {"0", "0", "1", "1", "0"}
    },
    GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
         Offset[0.7]}, 
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
        Offset[0.2], {
         Offset[0.4]}, 
        Offset[0.2]}}], "\[NoBreak]", ")"}],
  Function[BoxForm`e$, 
   MatrixForm[BoxForm`e$]]]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[82]= ",ExpressionUUID->"0e912e5d-8d45-4f93-b3f8-77a8455ac05c"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Noise stays in the tableau too. A named Pauli channel applied to a \
stabilizer state returns a probability-weighted mixture of stabilizer states, \
each branch an ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["O", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "84ba422b-c96a-42ee-b331-8831bdc5f5b7"],
 " tableau update rather than a dense density matrix. A bit-flip channel on \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5ca29f04-1604-49f0-909e-c1e04714df52"],
 " is the textbook example, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "546d3b6b-48e0-4d9c-886c-f94bea1fe24d"],
 " with probability ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "-", 
   StyleBox["p", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "12f48c19-5e9f-4b7c-85cc-71cba2fef51b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"1"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "42ee4fc3-d4d5-444e-b505-15a13df89eea"],
 " with probability ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["p", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c43a5a8b-0170-4603-a306-8673f402b11f"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cb66130a-3275-4593-a90d-70b674208b80"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"#1", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"#2", "[", "\"\<Stabilizers\>\"", "]"}]}], "}"}], " ", "&"}], 
  " ", "@@@", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"QuantumChannel", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<BitFlip\>\"", "[", 
     RowBox[{"1", "/", "10"}], "]"}], "]"}], "[", 
   RowBox[{"PauliStabilizer", "[", "1", "]"}], "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[83]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"244d3ea9-4ce3-413c-bdcf-10010feddc8a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["9", "10"], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", "\<\"Z\"\>", "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "10"], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", "\<\"-Z\"\>", "}"}]}], "}"}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[83]= ",ExpressionUUID->"79bdbe4c-d088-46a9-8359-950197b9883a"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The two branches are stabilized by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", 
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ab578449-fd4f-45e6-b829-a9ff8d1b664d"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", 
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e8ba995a-b31c-4926-8430-04b8ea18889b"],
 ", the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e43e1436-d92a-48be-8578-2fa0083c81d2"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"1"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6e3ac764-fa8e-4f7c-8f3f-18469dfc8f77"],
 " of a classical bit flip, with weights ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"9", "/", "10"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "64b62862-d3f1-4e45-bf91-05a2824c93c4"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "10"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3dfc5c5e-8478-4826-b7a2-8f24b45bfe11"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"17daf934-193d-4643-9587-09c4e1d4c288"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "These heads, together with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "4350465e-bfc5-4206-9900-f4ed093b10a6"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "StabilizerFrame"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "bacdec1a-21cf-4083-b39b-e7e5a50bae1a"],
 ", let one stay in the tableau picture for states, codes, graph-state \
surgery, magic accounting, and noise, inside the same object model as the \
rest of the framework."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4f7b33cd-4e84-4e3a-a947-98bca7172f95"],

Cell["An honest comparison with other packages", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e31ecdf3-d528-42c0-8bae-cb1680cceecd"],

Cell["\<\
The stabilizer simulators built for raw throughput are Stim, a C++ engine, \
and QuantumClifford.jl, a Julia package; both are excellent and both are \
narrower in scope than a general quantum framework. The fair question is \
two-sided: how close is the framework on the task they specialize in, and \
what does it offer that they do not.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6440765f-72b8-48dc-919d-daf6cdb8a281"],

Cell["\<\
On gate-folding throughput the gap is now a small constant factor. The \
figures below are the measured wall-clock for an identical Clifford stream on \
an Apple M2 Pro, measured June 2026 from the framework's own bottleneck \
audit, with Stim for reference; treat them as a dated snapshot, not a \
guarantee:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7fe06dff-d657-4d78-8767-6a8827abe927"],

Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {Cell["qubits (gates)", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"e5f17da3-8d8c-407f-9037-b99703e8385e"],
     Cell["QuantumFramework", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"9d6fe8f1-3ea7-4b07-a861-978d512faec0"],
     Cell["Stim", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"08eae5c6-7e25-47b6-96ae-b5ec6c823327"],
     Cell["ratio", "TableText",
     FontWeight->Bold,ExpressionUUID->"b6db4220-e78d-42db-ad90-0cd5c0c08916"]},
   {Cell["100 (2k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "e8e36d9f-ccbf-4f0a-a2d0-7c1baa39c756"], Cell[
    "2.6 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "ff9a07a4-9a73-4e34-a685-d928a4b61301"], Cell[
    "1.03 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "23e9215d-758f-43a0-9ca8-314717e75c4a"], Cell[
    "2.5x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "fa2a83a7-33fd-4818-8e95-9dd91f9ffa3d"]},
   {Cell["500 (10k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "f6a6793a-82c6-43e1-97b4-77a02b830bdd"], Cell[
    "26.2 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "0ced0c53-0a36-458a-bfd5-78037438a2ce"], Cell[
    "5.14 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "611a5f9e-48f1-4a33-8266-dd8a048b9877"], Cell[
    "5.1x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "09347306-66ff-4e39-9c0d-1730b105b5ff"]},
   {Cell["1000 (20k)", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "d82c67b4-b094-4afc-8f75-c1a8796a18f0"], Cell[
    "58.0 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "42d8ee93-ae93-4043-8415-17f088db4aed"], Cell[
    "10.9 ms", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "62d57130-a16d-4d29-a7bf-124e5cf52fb7"], Cell[
    "5.3x", "TableText",ExpressionUUID->
     "865f8f23-5708-41ef-917d-1109e39ef469"]}
  },
  GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
  GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {{None}}, "Rows" -> {{True}}},
  GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{1.5}}, "Rows" -> {{0.7}}}]], "Text",Express\
ionUUID->"5907647e-67db-4ac2-b3d7-d4897b4161a4"],

Cell["\<\
At a thousand qubits the framework also runs ahead of QuantumClifford.jl on \
the same stream (58.0 ms against 108.4 ms). The remaining gap to Stim is SIMD \
lane width, Stim packs 256-bit vector lanes against the framework's 62-bit \
machine words, plus a small per-gate circuit-encoding pass; it is a constant \
factor, not an algorithmic deficit. Getting there took compiling the gate \
fold to a single C kernel: the gate-by-gate interpreted path is 15 to 30 \
times slower, around 74, 402, and 955 ms at the three sizes above.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e64e4d24-4f86-48ec-8350-fbdc746b9dd5"],

Cell["What the framework offers that the dedicated engines do not:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"18c6b19c-7e2e-4d5b-8d25-c15debcf080d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Symbolic signs", "TI"],
 ". Outcomes can be carried as formal symbols through a circuit (the SymPhase \
method), so a single traversal serves arbitrarily many samples, and outcome \
correlations are explicit polynomials."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"19d1568a-45d7-4a00-a110-224408f1a2a5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Exact arithmetic", "TI"],
 ". Coefficients, signs, and the random-Clifford sampler use exact rationals, \
so seeded output is bit-reproducible and there is no floating-point drift."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6cf61e8d-135d-46cd-b8fe-800701617068"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["One object model", "TI"],
 ". A ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "971bab3b-1e94-46ae-b425-f75eba8548d8"],
 " converts to a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumState"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "55a66320-4d78-40de-8dcb-9b7f93b34643"],
 ", a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumOperator"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "00641fbe-5628-41f7-97e4-bce3457f8bad"],
 ", a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumCircuitOperator"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "ff4c4f20-1e06-4d75-86b6-0c38e9093f93"],
 ", or a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumChannel"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "7d9d17d4-01aa-486d-836a-4f882efe0f22"],
 ", so a stabilizer subroutine drops into a larger simulation that also uses \
dense states, density matrices, Lindblad evolution, or phase-space methods, \
without leaving the language."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"644a854e-9127-4aa8-8514-0d9827325b3b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Breadth of heads", "TI"],
 ". Graph states with local complementation, stabilizer frames for magic \
accounting, and Clifford channels for open-system Clifford dynamics are \
first-class objects, not features one bolts on."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"03dd7175-275a-4650-a7d1-1775286020a4"],

Cell["Where the framework genuinely trails, stated plainly:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1b659f61-9c0a-4437-866a-6a6d8da1971b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It is a constant factor (roughly ",
 Cell[BoxData["2.5"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c4ac3d0e-d055-40c9-b0af-909d27beae41"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"5.3", "\[Times]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "49bcd2af-6391-4ce8-8acb-5eaabc237d9e"],
 ") behind Stim on pure gate throughput, for the lane-width reason above."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4c2e8305-14e6-4c77-8a4d-c7d7521f5a8a"],

Cell["\<\
It has no constant-cost bulk Pauli-frame sampler, the trick that makes Stim's \
shot-by-shot sampling so cheap.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5fac52a0-b4d0-491e-b3f8-d97288042e36"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Constructing a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "QuantumCircuitOperator"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "7b4bb5db-de29-49b4-90ca-3b213f97d7ef"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["10", "4"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ba5fb1af-b112-42cd-9509-5bc526a762bf"],
 " or more gates carries host-framework overhead; for long streams one should \
hand the gate-spec list to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"ps", "[", "gates", "]"}]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "6f2b8f37-a770-4ec8-a30d-e7908c5bc11e"],
 " directly."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4bd272fc-b125-4613-b684-b6d391dcaf71"],

Cell["\<\
Reconstructing an exact state vector from a gate-updated tableau, or from a \
gate-built stabilizer frame, is correct up to a single global phase, which is \
never observable; only the relative phase between two separately-built \
objects is gauge-limited.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b74569f8-1288-4bf5-ad5b-c780adc1beb6"],

Cell["\<\
The summary is the one a physicist would want: for raw Clifford throughput \
the specialized engines are a few times faster, and if that is the only thing \
one needs, they are the right tool. For stabilizer simulation that has to \
interoperate with the rest of a quantum-mechanics toolkit, carry symbols, \
stay exact, and reach into codes, graph states, magic, and channels, the \
framework buys all of that for a small constant in speed.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0eca3d33-af42-495a-8aa9-bd60222490fd"],

Cell["Where this leaves us", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"31c21f70-cac4-49ad-898f-7ad4051a6f2b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We built the stabilizer formalism from one idea, that a state is named by \
what fixes it, and rode it from a single qubit to a thousand. Along the way \
the concrete tools were: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "PauliStabilizer"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "004c026a-235a-4beb-8fde-ae95e2aa5655"],
 " for states, codes, and the tableau; the gate-update methods and the \
circuit-list form ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"ps", "[", "gates", "]"}]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "54d3a69f-07e8-4dfe-8fab-85b07efffb89"],
 " for Clifford evolution; ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<M\>\""], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "a58a8bb6-5ac8-4b21-8dd8-03aed7032317"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<Expectation\>\""], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "3652c58e-d630-4f24-9c2a-155771f9fe30"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<SymbolicMeasure\>\""], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "d10606e2-9156-4b81-b0ae-c8150cb458f3"],
 " for measurement; ",
 Cell[BoxData["\"\<Entropy\>\""], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "aaf3769e-5355-4f10-b3cd-a72a2963e5db"],
 " for entanglement; ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"PauliStabilizer", "[", 
   RowBox[{"\"\<Random\>\"", "[", "n", "]"}], "]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"4fe2cabc-32c3-4149-acc1-be0c56eed462"],
 " for sampling; and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "GraphState"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "1ad482d9-9b0e-44e8-ab95-80f4042d7244"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "StabilizerFrame"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "c101dfe1-0065-4471-974b-3d319d213828"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "CliffordChannel"], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "74909f7a-7459-4590-b2df-291c2e037480"],
 " for the frontier."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"82977766-35aa-4ea0-8b7b-44c0d924a330"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The natural next steps are the ones the formalism opens onto: syndrome \
decoding on the codes of the error-correction section, stabilizer-rank \
simulation of magic-rich circuits via the frame, and Clifford-channel models \
of realistic noise. Each is a short extension of the computations above, and \
each stays, as long as it can, inside the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["O", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], "2"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "72598cb5-53c0-4f31-a08d-b729dac4dac3"],
 " tableau that makes the whole subject tractable."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b1d93edf-2af4-4ea6-b881-b9fc5dc9f993"],

Cell["\<\
The key references underpinning the implementation are Gottesman's \
stabilizer-codes thesis (1997), Aaronson and Gottesman on the tableau and its \
measurement update (2004), Fattal and collaborators on stabilizer \
entanglement entropy (2004), Anders and Briegel on graph states and local \
complementation (2005), Koenig and Smolin on the random-Clifford sampler \
(2014), Garcia and Markov on stabilizer frames (2015), Fang and Ying on \
symbolic phases (2023), and Yashin on Clifford channels (2025).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c6fee9f3-bb18-44b3-81b7-74426951d769"]
},
CreateCellID->True,
FrontEndVersion->"15.0 for Mac OS X ARM (64-bit) (February 17, 2026)",
StyleDefinitions->"Default.nb",
ExpressionUUID->"2808c5c8-faec-4c5e-84f7-3f99d205e893"
]
